ties and intimacies of personal experience. The framework of racial identity constructed through these stories proves instrumental in explaining how countries later confronted-or not-the legacy of the slave trade. Today, these vocabularies of slavery live on for contemporary refugees whose forced migrations often replicate the journeys and stigmas faced by slaves in the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aSlaveryzEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzSudanxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzTurkeyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveszEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveszSudanxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveszTurkeyxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478375040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804783750.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles